5|$|Hong Kong's {{de facto}} {{official}} language is Cantonese, {{a variety of}} Chinese originating from Guangdong province {{to the north of}} Hong Kong. According to the 2016 by-census, Cantonese is spoken by 94.6% of the Hong Kong population; 88.9 percent as a first language and 5.7% <b>as</b> <b>a</b> <b>second</b> <b>language.</b> English is also an official language, and according to the 2016 by-census is spoken by 53.2% of the population; 4.3 percent as a first language and 48.9 percent <b>as</b> <b>a</b> <b>second</b> <b>language.</b> Signs displaying both Chinese and English are common throughout the territory. Since the 1997 Handover, an increase in immigrants from mainland China and greater interaction with the mainland's economy have brought an increasing number of Mandarin speakers to Hong Kong. According to the 2016 by-census, Mandarin is spoken by 48.6% of the population; 1.9 percent as a first language and 46.7 percent <b>as</b> <b>a</b> <b>second</b> <b>language.</b>|$|E
